config.comments:
This processor is to get a lot of submission from the datacenter MySQL instance.
Offset is really slow in MySQL when the offset becomes large, so instead this is just a hand crafted query on submissions table.
Typically a month of submissions is like 2GB of AVRO, which NiFi handles okay.

entry.value: SELECT * FROM submissions WHERE created_at >= '2024-08-01 00:00:00' AND created_at < '2024-09-01 00:00:00'

SELECT get_fullname_by_user_id(${user_id}) AS user, get_form_version_by_id(${form_id}) AS form_version, get_form_type_by_id(${form_id}) AS form_type, get_form_uuid_by_id(${form_id}) AS form_uuid, get_username_by_user_id(${user_id}) AS username, get_manager_by_user_id(${user_id}) AS manager, get_line_manager_by_user_id(${user_id}) AS line_manager, get_regional_manager_by_user_id(${user_id}) AS regional_manager, get_outlet_name_by_id(${outlet_id}) AS meta_outlet_name;

config.comments:
We now have the Kafka topics in a table in Postgres, so if we have not created an Ingestion job in Druid for that topic (and the company name is not TEST OR DEMO) we should do that.
The script processor creates the JSON payload that we POST to the API, this is where we control the 'specs' of the ingestion job

entry.value: WITH rm_test AS ( SELECT ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY uuid ORDER BY f.updated_at DESC) rn, topic, k.id --c.name FROM kafka_topics k INNER JOIN forms f ON k.topic = f.uuid --INNER JOIN companies c ON c.id = f.company_id WHERE is_processing = FALSE AND is_ingesting = FALSE AND f.company_id NOT IN ( ( SELECT id FROM companies WHERE (UPPER(name) LIKE '%TEST%' OR UPPER(name) LIKE '%DEMO%') ) ) ) SELECT topic, id FROM rm_test WHERE rn = 1;

config.comments:
This processors queries the MySQL read replica in Azure tracking the created_at column for latest submissions.
The data is then split into individual records, flattened, lookups are done in Postgres and eventually the record is put on a kafka topic, the topic name is the form uuid.

entry.value: SELECT --get_form_uuid_by_id(form_id) source, uuid AS source, count(*) dwh_total, s.created_at::timestamp::date date_checked FROM submissions s LEFT JOIN forms f ON s.form_id = f.id WHERE s.created_at::timestamp::date < now()::timestamp::date AND s.created_at::timestamp::date > (SELECT date_checked FROM druid_compare ORDER BY date_checked DESC LIMIT 1) --AND s.created_at::timestamp::date >= '2024-08-01' GROUP BY uuid, s.created_at::timestamp::date;

config.comments: The Kafka Topics are created automagically by the NiFi Kafka processor, however we now need to keep track of the topics are the Druid ingestion jobs need to be created. So we use the a Kafka client located on the NiFi VM to query the Kafka cluster and get all the topics in the cluster.
